Revised test suite from thigh phantom

W. Bauer

October 24, 2015

This note adds to the suite of test data set constructed here. The earlier set assumed a probe width of 3 cm which is incorrect. The correct value of 6 cm is used here.

As before, the first task was to identify rectangular sections. This was a trial and error process, performed off-line. Resulting sections are shown below in various colors. All are 30 mm in height, which is approximately that of a 128 element ultrasound probe.

Controlling an image’s height in pixels is a bit tricky. The following checks a calculation to do so.

Several minutes of run time were required to produce pixelated images. Hence, the suite was produced off line by the following code. Pixels were labeled by tissue type so that speeds of sound can be varied dynamically. The images themselves are in this project’s data subdirectory and are identified by the prefix, “wide”, the scan number, and the resolution. For instance, wide_scan_6_64.csv corresponds to the 6th rectangular section with a grid size corresponding to 64 transducers spread over a 30 cm height. Scan 6 is shown at 4 resolutions below.

datadir = "../data"
scans <- paste0("scan_",1:8)
for(n in 1:8){
  scan <- get(scans[n])
  for(res in 2^(4:7)){
    gridsize <- calcGridSize(scan, res)
    img <- pixelate(phantom, scan, gridsize)
    colnames(img) <- as.character(signif(gridsize*(1:ncol(img)-1),4))
    outf <- paste0(datadir,"/wide_",scans[n],"_",res,".csv")
    write.csv(as.data.frame(img),outf, row.names=FALSE)
    writeLines(outf)
  }
}
